name: Tessia
description:
Task Execution Supporter and System Installation Assistant

A tool to automate and simplify the installation/configuration/testing of Linux systems running on the IBM Z platform.

Main functions available in the tool:

- Automatic installation and management of Linux operating systems on IBM Z machines
- Datacenter resources management: storage servers, volumes, network subnets, ip addresses
- Job scheduling for automatic execution of tasks/scripts
- Command line client and REST-like API
- Role based permission model
contribution_justification: All contributions are made in a separate branch and the contributor opens a merge/pull request for it to trigger code review. After code review from project maintainers the patch is accepted or improvements are suggested. Detailed process is described in https://gitlab.com/tessia-project/tessia/-/blob/master/doc/developers/contributing.md
license_location_justification: https://gitlab.com/tessia-project/tessia/-/blob/master/LICENSE
floss_license_justification: All contributors agree to publish their code under specified license (commits are signed with DCO): https://gitlab.com/tessia-project/tessia/blob/master/DCO1.1.txt The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: https://gitlab.com/tessia-project/tessia/-/tree/master/doc
documentation_interface_justification: An extensive "users" section provides general guidance on installation, configuration, "how-to"s and complete usage examples: https://gitlab.com/tessia-project/tessia/-/tree/master/doc/users
repo_interim_justification: All code review is done on separate branches through merge/pull requests
repo_distributed_justification: Git is used as the version control system
version_tags_justification: Git tags are used for marking releases
release_notes_justification: For every release a manual summary is added to https://gitlab.com/tessia-project/tessia/-/blob/master/doc/releases.md and GitLab and GitHub release pages.
release_notes_vulns_justification: There have been no publicly known vulnerabilities
report_process_justification: As described in https://gitlab.com/tessia-project/tessia/-/blob/master/README.md , bug reports may be submitted through repository issue tracker.
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: As described in https://gitlab.com/tessia-project/tessia/-/blob/master/README.md , private reports may be sent through private mailing list.
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: There have been no vulnerabilities reported in the last 6 months
build_justification: A custom orchestrator is provided for building, testing and deploying the product: https://gitlab.com/tessia-project/tessia/-/blob/master/tools/ci/orc
build_common_tools_justification: A custom orchestrating tool is easier to maintain
test_justification: A set of tests is provided with the source, and ways to run different types of tests are described in https://gitlab.com/tessia-project/tessia/-/blob/master/doc/developers/tests.md
test_invocation_justification:
Unit tests can be run in a standard way, but they often rely on a database instance to be available.
End-to-end tests require a complete deployment and are driven by the provided orchestrator.
test_most_justification: Contribution guidelines require unit tests to be provided for new functionality. In addition, low output from "coverage" provided by test output is sternly frowned upon.
test_policy_justification: Contribution guidelines require unit tests to be provided for new functionality, with a separate guide on how to write unit and integration tests: https://gitlab.com/tessia-project/tessia/-/blob/master/doc/developers/tests.md
tests_documented_added_justification: A separate guide on how to write unit and integration tests is present: https://gitlab.com/tessia-project/tessia/-/blob/master/doc/developers/tests.md
warnings_justification: Pylint is used for static code analysis.
know_secure_design_justification: Both project maintainer and primary developer are acquainted with the contents of SSDF course.
delivery_mitm_justification: The product is built from source
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: Mostly relying on static analysis and code review, but will revisit this point later.
dynamic_analysis_justification: Mostly relying on static analysis and code review, but will revisit this point later.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: Will revisit using dynamic tools for unit tests
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: GitLab CI is run on commits and merge requests.
discussion_justification: Repository issues and mailing lists are open for discussions
